# Introduction
The trend toward miniaturization in microelectronics and the emerging field of nanotechnology require understanding material properties of smaller and smaller volumes of material. In microelectronics, the device dimension is becoming so small that a 0.5 μm "crack" leads to device failure. Due to the heterogeneity of the device, this failure process occurs in a small volume of material or along an interface of small spatial extent. In nanotechnology, one aims at building nanostructures and nanomachines whose design is impossible without the fundamental understanding of the mechanical behavior of materials at the nanoscale. In this program we investigate some key nanoscale mechanical properties such as size effects of strength, rate sensitivity and plasticity.

Most such data were obtained before by using surface probes, in particular, nanoindentation. In this test, the deformation is governed by a small number of crystal defects and the statistics that leads to the macroscopic bulk plastic behavior is not reproduced. Although useful for principle demonstration, the test poses some challenges in data interpretation. The limitation stems from the nature of loading of the material nanovolume; the nanoindenter induces steep stress gradients and the "tested volume" is not well defined.

To date, most work on individual (isolated) nanoscale structures has focused on carbon nanotubes, very thin films and nanowires. There appears to be agreement in the literature regarding the scaling of the plastic behavior: the yield stress increases with decreasing specimen dimensions. The scaling of the yield stress is attributed to two effects: presence of strain gradients, and "dislocation starvation." This second effect leads to size effects even in absence of strain gradients, e.g in vertical pillars subjected to compression. The phenomenon consists in the fact that, in small specimens, the residence time of dislocations in the material is short. Once the pre-existing dislocations leave the specimen, new ones have to be created to sustain plastic deformation.

The work performed as part of this project aims at using a novel nanoscale material testing technique to study the size effect in several mechanical material properties, size effect associated with reducing specimen dimensions in the nanoscale range. We are using a new class of isolated nanostructures specially designed to allow us to control the stress state in the specimen and reproduce the macroscopic tests at the nanoscale.

# Approach
Part of the novelty of the proposed work consists in the use of special nanostructures designed for the purpose of measuring mechanical properties at the nanoscale. These structures (Fig. 2) are in the form of nanobeams (and structures of beams) and nanosprings with controlled nanometer scale dimensions. They are currently fabricated in our lab by the oblique angle deposition technique. These structures provide the advantage that the volume of material tested is well defined AND the stress state in the structure is controlled. Specifically, we design the shape of the specimens using finite element analysis in order to obtain a desired stress state and then we grow them to these specifications. The oblique angle deposition technique uses the shadowing effect during growth. By this, some of the incident particles do not reach certain points of the substrate due to the concurrent growth of parallel structures. The shadowing effect is controlled by adjusting the incidence angle ?, while rotating the substrate, as shown schematically in Fig. 1. Such set-ups may be used with evaporation as well as with sputtering.

