<b>Figure 7:</b>  Wohler-type curve for the nanorods in Fig. 3. The data points indicate failure under cyclic loading. A pronounced fatigue susceptibility is shown.
</figcaption>
</figure>


## Electro-mechanical Actuation at the Nanoscale
Electromechanical actuation was demonstrated at the nanoscale using the four-turn Si nanosprings in Fig. 4. Si springs were rendered conductive by coating with a 10 nm-thick Co layer by chemical vapor deposition. A dc current was passed through the spring which behaves as a solenoid. A conductive AFM tip was used for this purpose. The electromagnetic force between the wires of the spring leads to spring compression, which is measured with the same AFM tip. This is possible because the tip is in contact mode continuously touching the nanostructure. A schematic of the set-up is shown in Fig. 8.

