## Nanostructures used as Compliant Layers to Reduce Residual Stresses in Films
 We developed a method to significantly reduce the residual stress in W films by growing the films on an un-structured layer of slanted W nanorods. Specifically, a 50 nm thick layer of W nanorods is first deposited on the bare substrate (say, Si) by glancing angle deposition. Since the rods do not grow on a template (as in the figures shown above), nucleation is random and the density of nanostructures is high. Once the compliant layer is deposited, the growth conditions are returned to normal and a regular continuous W film is deposited. The residual stress on this film is much smaller than that in the same film grown directly on the bare substrate. This allows growing thicker films before buckling.


Figure 9 shows an image of a buckled 240 nm thick film grown directly on the substrate, and that of an intact film of same thickness grown on the compliant layer. Figure 10 shows a cross-section through an un-buckled 1.8 microns thick W film formed from a sandwich of 3 normal films and 3 compliant layers.

